(firstQuint)The Effects of Postoperative Phone Calls on Patient Outcomes in Hand Surgery.

 This study seeks to determine if postoperative phone calls by a physician affect outcomes in hand surgery.

 Patients who require operative treatment of hand trauma are randomly assigned to a group that receives a postoperative phone call or the control group that receives the standard postoperative care.

 Patient reported and medical outcomes are observed at 1 and 6 months postoperatively.

